196065.description:
You are expert in document processing with a focus on extracting critical information from passports. Your task is to extract the value associated with "Date of Issue" in the format present in the document as it is which specifies when the passport was officially issued.
Note :
1) Do not consider "Date of Issue" from old passport number.
2) Ignore any variations such as "Issue date", "Date Issue", "RP Issue date" etc.
3) If the "Date of issue" cannot be found, return N/A.

lines.prompt:
Step-1 : If the extracted value is 'N/A' or empty, return 'N/A'.

Step-2 : If the extracted value does not contain 3 parts, then return the extracted value as it is.

Step-3 : Otherwise, Maintain the extracted date format as it is, but just convert the month (second part in the extracted date) to English format.

Step-4 : Make sure the month(second part in the date) appears only once in the extracted date.

Let's think step by step

54091.description:
eturn the first name or given names of the person for whom the passport is issued.

Include the middle name from the middle name column if it exists, as it is typically mentioned below the given name.

Given name may or may not include one or more names.

If the names are in a single line, assume the last word is the surname or is mentioned below it.

Return only the Given Name(s), with no additional explanation or text.
54091.name: Given Name
54091.prompt:
Extract the Given Name(s) of the Passport Holder 
Return the given name(s) (i.e., first name and middle name, if present) of the person to whom the passport is issued.
If the "Given Name(s)" field is provided separately from the "Surname", return the full value of "Given Name(s)" as-it is.
If the full name appears on a single line.
Return all words as the given name(s).
If only one word is present in the name treat it as given name.

Example: 
1. Given name: 
JOSE MARI, Middle name: DELA CRUZ
then given name is: JOSE MARI

2.  Full name: 
NADIA EMILE MIKHAEL HANNA
then given name is: NADIA EMILE MIKHAEL 

3. Full name: OMNIA MOHAMED FOUAD ALY IBRAHIM 
GALAL
then given name is: OMNIA MOHAMED FOUAD ALY IBRAHIM GALAL

4. Full name: ANANDANAYAGAM SHARVANANDAN
then given name is: ANANDANAYAGAM.

5. Full name: VINCY PARANGOTTUKANDATHIL MATHAI SAMUEL
then given name is: VINCY PARANGOTTUKANDATHIL MATHAI

6.  Full name: MOTAZ ABDELRAZZAQ SALAMEH ALMA'ANI
then given name is: MOTAZ ABDELRAZZAQ SALAMEH

54093.description: Mostly surname is mentioned above given name. If it is in a single line the "last" word is the surname or mentioned below it. It can include two or more words.
54093.name: Surname
54093.prompt:
Extract the surname (last name or family name) from the passport using the following rules:

Look for a field labeled "Surname", "Apelyido", "Nom", or similar. Return the exact full value.

If "Surname" and "Given Name(s)" are in separate fields, extract only the Surname value—even if it's multiple words. If not clearly separated, return "N/A".

Do not return middle names, given names, or maiden names.

Use the MRZ (Machine Readable Zone) if printed fields are unclear. Take the word between the country code and the first < as the surname.

If no surname is found, return "N/A".

Ensure correct spelling as written in the document. Do not assume, correct, or modify names.

📌 Examples:
• Name: ANANDANAYAGAM SHARVANANDAN → Return: SHARVANANDAN
• Surname: CADORES, Given name: FRANCIS → Return: CADORES
• MRZ: PHLGALITO<<ALBERTO<JR → Return: GALITO
❌ Do not return: GALING, ACAYAN, or guessed names.


Return only the surname. No extra text.

54097.description:
Extract the nationality of the passport holder using the rules below:

Look for a field labeled “Nationality”, “Nationalité”, or similar.

Return the exact English word written under this field.
• If both local and English terms are present (e.g., “Française / French”), return only the English word → “French”.

Do not translate, guess, or shorten the value.

Do not return any labels, extra text, or personal information.

If the nationality field is missing or unreadable, return "N/A".

Correct Examples:
• Nationality: French → Return: French
• Nationality: Filipino → Return: Filipino
• Nationality: JOR → Return: JORDAN (keep as-is if it's the official format shown)

❌ Do not return:
• “Nationality: Filipino” → ❌ Only return → Filipino
• “Française” → ❌ Return → French

lines.prompt:
If the field contains both local and English terms (e.g., “SVENSK SWEDISH”),
return only the English value (e.g., “Swedish”).
